1
00:00:08,535 --> 00:00:36,804
namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa

2
00:00:37,325 --> 00:00:41,792
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:48,243 --> 00:00:59,383
Yeah, I was just going to talk about this confusion sometimes that people have between paññā, insight.

4
00:00:59,515 --> 00:01:03,121
the awakening, and sila, conduct.

5
00:01:04,862 --> 00:01:10,492
So I think it's still in some circles when you say morality, it sort of gets people very angry.

6
00:01:12,516 --> 00:01:16,481
They don't want to know about morality as such, or the ethical life.

7
00:01:20,849 --> 00:01:27,379
In the chant in the morning, you see, we say of the Buddha that he's vijja-carna-sampanno, that he's accomplished.

8
00:01:28,371 --> 00:01:52,793
both in his understanding and in his conduct and he himself says that understanding and conduct are like the Ganges and the Yamuna rivers that join and flow into the sea he doesn't make a distinction between understanding and how it expresses itself

9
00:01:56,602 --> 00:02:10,959
Some of you will know that the Eightfold Path is normally split into three sections, sila, samādhi, paññā, right conduct, right meditation, samādhi, and right understanding.

10
00:02:12,640 --> 00:02:19,168
And that samādhi normally usually refers to the absorptions.

11
00:02:22,405 --> 00:02:48,514
but in the Buddha's teachings those are not actually necessary so that the whole teaching can be reduced in terms of the process of purification and awakening to those two words, paññā and sila paññā is this business of trying to understand how things really are and sila is right conduct, ethical behavior

12
00:02:52,627 --> 00:02:54,711
Those two sum up the Buddha's teachings.

13
00:02:56,353 --> 00:02:59,116
But then you'll come across writers who sort of split them.

14
00:02:59,616 --> 00:03:12,312
And when you go to the East and you see how people behave, you can understand how they might come to these conclusions from their fieldwork, from their anthropological fieldwork.

15
00:03:12,332 --> 00:03:18,180
And one writer talks about Nibbanic Buddhism and Karmic Buddhism.

16
00:03:20,437 --> 00:03:36,299
So, often when you speak to Eastern Buddhists, or born Buddhists anyway, they won't have a doubt that the end point is to become liberated, Nibbāna, and that's the point.

17
00:03:37,199 --> 00:03:42,687
But their whole life is really centered around sila, which is right conduct.

18
00:03:44,229 --> 00:03:48,555
And when you follow that train of thought through,

19
00:03:49,564 --> 00:04:00,135
they're not concerned so much with getting rid of this self, but more in the sense of making it a good self, a happy self, insofar as the self can be happy.

20
00:04:02,558 --> 00:04:13,531
And so their whole lives are about doing right things, and this is where the word kusala comes in, in order to gain merit, and that's punya.

21
00:04:13,550 --> 00:04:19,437
These two words, kusala and punya, are also key words in the Buddha's teachings.

22
00:04:21,002 --> 00:04:30,696
And the general idea is that you stop doing harm, you do as much good as you can, and you get reborn in the heavenly realm.

23
00:04:33,038 --> 00:04:45,295
And in the heavenly realm, it's a little easier to seek Nibbāna.

24
00:04:45,454 --> 00:04:50,622
Even amongst monks and nuns, you'll find that that is the prevalent attitude.

25
00:04:52,103 --> 00:05:09,079
And you'll find the monks in Sri Lanka, I'm not so sure about Burma and Thailand and other places, but being influenced by Hinduism, the hierarchy will tell you that this is the Kala Yoga.

26
00:05:10,100 --> 00:05:15,146
And it's impossible for anybody to become enlightened during this particular time, so forget it.

27
00:05:16,107 --> 00:05:19,730
The best thing you can do is to do good and get reborn into a better place.

28
00:05:22,427 --> 00:05:23,529
It's a bit disheartening, really.

29
00:05:25,774 --> 00:05:26,637
But they're happy with that.

30
00:05:28,100 --> 00:05:29,122
In a sense, it's a let-out.

31
00:05:29,223 --> 00:05:33,973
I mean, if you say to yourself, I can't become enlightened, phew, you know, I may as well enjoy myself.

32
00:05:36,117 --> 00:05:37,300
That's the case.

33
00:05:37,319 --> 00:05:40,706
So, you've got to be careful with that sort of mentality.

34
00:05:47,081 --> 00:06:03,233
But both in the actual, the way the Buddha behaves, his actual behavior, and in the general teachings, and even in the psychology, what we chant in the morning, we have been originated.

35
00:06:04,535 --> 00:06:07,199
You can begin to see that you can't split the one from the other.

36
00:06:07,420 --> 00:06:09,764
The one arises out of the other.

37
00:06:16,411 --> 00:06:31,454
There's this point in the Buddha's life of once he's become enlightened, once he's become liberated and he has this deep understanding into the way things are and he spends some time recollecting over it.

38
00:06:32,035 --> 00:06:37,524
Mythically it's said three nights he goes through this wheel of dependent origination, forward, backward, both forward and backward.

39
00:06:38,004 --> 00:06:43,312
But obviously he sat there and that insight had to permeate his understanding.

40
00:06:44,507 --> 00:07:05,757
and he came up with this and then at that point there is this idea arise in his head to you know who can he teach who can he teach so that has arisen spontaneously in his mind now when he looks around and

41
00:07:06,562 --> 00:07:10,992
He sees through his powers that his old teachers have died.

42
00:07:11,632 --> 00:07:12,615
And he gets the doubt.

43
00:07:12,935 --> 00:07:15,661
And the doubt is that anybody can receive this teaching.

44
00:07:15,841 --> 00:07:16,603
It's too subtle.

45
00:07:17,084 --> 00:07:18,908
He doesn't believe for a moment there.

46
00:07:18,927 --> 00:07:20,791
He doesn't think that people are ready for this.

47
00:07:22,966 --> 00:07:33,079
Now you'll find in some writers that they call this the great hesitation, and they argue that therefore the Buddha's accomplishment is twofold.

48
00:07:33,098 --> 00:07:43,872
His accomplishment was both the enlightenment, his liberation, and secondly his teaching, and that he need not necessarily have taught.

49
00:07:43,892 --> 00:07:51,423
He could have said, no, I won't, I'll sit here in this bliss until I pop off.

50
00:07:51,442 --> 00:07:51,622
Yes?

51
00:07:53,324 --> 00:08:04,160
And that's where you get some idea that perhaps there's a choice, that you can become liberated and yet not do anything.

52
00:08:11,550 --> 00:08:14,535
That it doesn't manifest outwardly into the world.

53
00:08:17,839 --> 00:08:21,846
Supporting that is that myth of the Pacheco Buddha, the private Buddha.

54
00:08:22,500 --> 00:08:48,153
private the person who's become fully liberated but what it really says about that is that they can't teach that's the normal thing not that they don't want to they just can't they don't have the skills or the capacity and if you think of just ordinary life sometimes you get people don't you who are very clever in their subject but they just can't get it across

55
00:08:50,277 --> 00:09:15,407
so that's another skill so in the sense that the Buddha had a special skill whereby he could actually get this stuff across to people is one thing but the hesitation was only around this is just my own understanding the hesitation was only around whether people were actually ready to receive it the hesitation wasn't in whether to teach or not

56
00:09:17,394 --> 00:09:18,876
Which is a distinction, isn't it?

57
00:09:19,817 --> 00:09:29,672
So the desire to teach, the desire to actually share what he had with others, arose spontaneously after he had understood what it was that he had gained.

58
00:09:31,774 --> 00:09:36,500
In the Zen tradition, you'll hear it said that with wisdom, compassion arises naturally.

59
00:09:39,264 --> 00:09:45,072
So it's not possible to continue in the path

60
00:09:45,239 --> 00:09:47,240
and for our behavior not to change.

61
00:09:48,643 --> 00:09:54,909
To take it at a ridiculous level, you couldn't have a neurotic Buddha.

62
00:09:56,390 --> 00:09:59,153
That would be awful, wouldn't it?

63
00:09:59,174 --> 00:10:01,957
Worrying about his fingernails while he's teaching.

64
00:10:03,720 --> 00:10:05,260
Worrying whether he'll be liked.

65
00:10:07,943 --> 00:10:09,846
Worrying whether he'll get any food today.

66
00:10:11,707 --> 00:10:14,892
It doesn't sit, does it?

67
00:10:15,326 --> 00:10:17,250
And it would be awful if he were immoral.

68
00:10:17,971 --> 00:10:24,163
He's sort of teaching all this stuff and going around robbing banks.

69
00:10:24,182 --> 00:10:36,846
So there's something that jars when you sort of consider what the behavior of somebody who is spiritually advanced might be if it doesn't connect with understanding.

70
00:10:37,062 --> 00:10:43,009
there's got to be that immediate connection between a person's understanding and purity.

71
00:10:43,230 --> 00:10:45,913
I mean, the whole point is that there's a purification of the heart going on.

72
00:10:47,216 --> 00:11:05,600
So here we are, we're meditating, we're doing this vipassana, and we can see that, A, there's this insight going on, there's this understanding about ourselves and how we're creating suffering for ourselves, but there's also this purification going on.

73
00:11:06,846 --> 00:11:15,917
that in fact, you know, we are getting less and less depressed, less and less angry, or at least not for such a long period.

74
00:11:16,717 --> 00:11:18,720
You know, and there's a certain progression.

75
00:11:21,023 --> 00:11:26,708
If you're not progressing, then you have to look at your practice and find out why.

76
00:11:27,429 --> 00:11:28,250
Because that's the point.

77
00:11:28,291 --> 00:11:33,275
The point is to progress, both in understanding and in our...

78
00:11:35,634 --> 00:11:37,657
happiness, our contentedness.

79
00:11:43,121 --> 00:11:58,615
So, that business of the slow gaining of understanding into the way we are, manifesting as good action, is right there in the Noble Eightfold Path.

80
00:11:58,796 --> 00:12:00,136
It flows right down.

81
00:12:00,297 --> 00:12:03,600
So, right understanding changes your attitude to life.

82
00:12:05,892 --> 00:12:10,035
So for the Buddha, once the understanding had come, the compassion arose.

83
00:12:10,417 --> 00:12:17,985
And he himself is constantly saying, ānukāpā, he says, out of empathy, out of sympathy, I teach you.

84
00:12:18,865 --> 00:12:21,489
Whatever a teacher can do for his students, I've done for you.

85
00:12:21,528 --> 00:12:31,379
And then that manifests, right speech, right action, right livelihood.

86
00:12:31,859 --> 00:12:34,261
Right speech, right action, right livelihood.

87
00:12:37,432 --> 00:12:39,735
Now, we also know that it can go back the other way.

88
00:12:40,475 --> 00:12:45,101
Depending on your livelihood, you yourself can be changed, can't you?

89
00:12:45,121 --> 00:12:52,591
I mean, just imagine now, you know, if we all joined the SAS.

90
00:12:55,515 --> 00:12:57,138
The Special Army Services.

91
00:12:59,200 --> 00:12:59,941
It would be different, wouldn't it?

92
00:13:01,823 --> 00:13:05,869
I mean, you'd be out there with your machine gun.

93
00:13:06,743 --> 00:13:10,792
waiting to kill somebody, or at least protecting yourself.

94
00:13:10,812 --> 00:13:12,615
So your whole mentality would change, wouldn't it?

95
00:13:12,995 --> 00:13:19,350
Or if you, like a policeman, a policeman's always suspicious.

96
00:13:20,893 --> 00:13:22,355
A policeman walks in here, he'd be suspicious.

97
00:13:24,479 --> 00:13:31,590
I have my brother-in-law in special service.

98
00:13:31,970 --> 00:13:32,951
He protects politicians.

99
00:13:33,491 --> 00:13:35,195
He's always suspicious.

100
00:13:36,417 --> 00:13:39,741
He's got to be.

101
00:13:39,761 --> 00:13:40,903
He's trained to be suspicious.

102
00:13:40,943 --> 00:13:41,965
He wanted to be suspicious.

103
00:13:44,808 --> 00:13:47,513
A teacher never asks a question they don't know the answer.

104
00:13:49,677 --> 00:13:53,322
They always make sure they know the answer.

105
00:13:54,009 --> 00:13:59,284
What we do affects us, doesn't it, directly?

106
00:13:59,686 --> 00:14:09,994
Our personality, the way we speak, our friendships, our acquaintances, what politics we follow.

107
00:14:09,974 --> 00:14:19,491
what particular religion we follow, all that sort of has an effect on us and produces a certain way of behaving, but it also comes with an understanding.

108
00:14:19,751 --> 00:14:27,888
And that understanding is either going to take us into further happiness or further unhappiness.

109
00:14:28,048 --> 00:14:30,091
So it runs both ways.

110
00:14:31,759 --> 00:14:50,562
through our understanding which is at three levels of actually hearing something which has an effect on us that we haven't heard before, through our own mental processes, our own reflection, and then through this direct insight, through direct experience.

111
00:14:51,857 --> 00:14:53,360
So our understanding changes.

112
00:14:55,004 --> 00:14:56,769
But it can also change by what we do.

113
00:14:56,808 --> 00:15:02,500
So there's an intimate relationship between our conduct and our understanding.

114
00:15:04,985 --> 00:15:07,250
It would be false to separate that.

115
00:15:15,888 --> 00:15:31,711
So when you understand that, you see, in lay life, because most of the time you have to be doing something, your job, whatever it is, you can really see quite clearly that this is the path, the path of action.

116
00:15:33,995 --> 00:15:39,263
What we're actually doing at any present time, at any present moment, is a path leading us

117
00:15:39,596 --> 00:15:43,802
either towards or away from this liberation.

118
00:15:44,865 --> 00:15:53,677
And therefore, anytime we do something, there is the importance of that moment of reflection about whether it's kussala or akussala.

119
00:15:55,460 --> 00:16:01,227
Now this word kussala, it has two meanings in English.

120
00:16:01,889 --> 00:16:03,410
One is that it's skillful.

121
00:16:05,077 --> 00:16:21,014
Unfortunately, if you say, well, I'm only doing this because it's skillful, I'm only being good, I'm only being generous and compassionate because it's skillful, then, as it were, the action is taken off the action itself for some future purpose.

122
00:16:21,134 --> 00:16:24,256
So I'm being skillful now, so I can be liberated later.

123
00:16:25,357 --> 00:16:32,065
And immediately you cut in between these two processes, paññā and sila.

124
00:16:32,585 --> 00:16:35,708
So it becomes a sort of utilitarian thing.

125
00:16:35,929 --> 00:16:39,173
I'm only being good so that I can become enlightened.

126
00:16:39,495 --> 00:16:43,700
I'm only helping you so that I can become... See what I mean?

127
00:16:43,820 --> 00:16:44,621
There's a split there.

128
00:16:46,604 --> 00:16:50,369
So now you'll often see in the books that that word is translated as skillful.

129
00:16:50,730 --> 00:16:51,671
But that's the danger.

130
00:16:51,711 --> 00:16:56,398
And it means that a sealer itself is not an end in itself.

131
00:16:58,100 --> 00:17:02,405
But in fact, you know, the end in this life is...

132
00:17:02,690 --> 00:17:10,719
perfect conduct, vijja-carna-sampanno, perfected, accomplished in his understanding and his behavior.

133
00:17:12,540 --> 00:17:21,009
So, although we might say skillful in the sense that it's wholesome and it's right and all that, you also have to use the word virtuous.

134
00:17:21,029 --> 00:17:25,015
It is virtuous as opposed to being non-virtuous or vicious.

135
00:17:26,096 --> 00:17:30,079
And the question is, is virtue an end in itself?

136
00:17:31,362 --> 00:17:31,481
Is it?

137
00:17:32,186 --> 00:17:34,150
Is the virtuous life an end in itself?

138
00:17:35,832 --> 00:17:39,115
Now, you wouldn't be virtuous if you look at it the other way.

139
00:17:39,155 --> 00:17:44,383
You wouldn't be virtuous unless you knew why you're being virtuous.

140
00:17:44,683 --> 00:17:46,105
There has to be an insight into it.

141
00:17:46,987 --> 00:17:48,648
It needn't be an intellectual insight.

142
00:17:49,210 --> 00:17:53,976
It needn't be something that you can scribble on a piece of paper.

143
00:17:56,098 --> 00:18:07,894
when we feel a certain compassion towards somebody, when we want to help somebody, when that feeling comes out, the underlying understanding there is our interrelatedness.

144
00:18:09,915 --> 00:18:17,144
So although we can talk about interrelatedness from this high intellectual level,

145
00:18:18,037 --> 00:18:26,446
about how things all fit together, about how things are related to each other, everything is conditioned by everything else and all that.

146
00:18:28,429 --> 00:18:42,204
The actual experience of it in terms of our relationship to other beings, and to plants and the earth and all that, is this heart relationship of compassion, love, sympathetic joy,

147
00:18:44,917 --> 00:18:46,400
And that's a heart understanding.

148
00:18:46,839 --> 00:18:51,746
If you split the two, then you move towards a sort of dry intellectual understanding.

149
00:18:52,646 --> 00:18:54,107
And you miss out on the heart level.

150
00:18:55,349 --> 00:19:02,998
On the other hand, if you stick with the heart level without some sort of understanding, then it can so easily slip into sort of mawkish behavior.

151
00:19:05,240 --> 00:19:11,667
So that's where we were saying last time about the slippage of compassion into pity or grief.

152
00:19:28,625 --> 00:19:38,256
Now when we have this word kusala, this word virtuous or skillful, there's always this follow-on of punya, which translates as merit.

153
00:19:39,657 --> 00:19:46,786
And it begins to sound a bit like some Christian doctrines, like grace.

154
00:19:47,807 --> 00:19:51,932
And you'll often hear in Buddhist circles

155
00:19:52,434 --> 00:19:58,142
You know, bone Buddhists, cultural Buddhists, I don't know what you call them.

156
00:19:58,241 --> 00:19:59,163
It's like a bank account.

157
00:19:59,344 --> 00:20:04,230
You've got all this merit, and you can draw on it at any time, and you can share it with people.

158
00:20:05,872 --> 00:20:09,175
And that's meritorious, so you get more merit because you've shared your merit.

159
00:20:09,896 --> 00:20:14,342
It's a sort of bank account that manufactures itself, which is wonderful, isn't it?

160
00:20:17,005 --> 00:20:25,175
But when you actually read the psychology of the Buddha, this punya has nothing to do with the outside.

161
00:20:25,215 --> 00:20:27,358
Of course the outside might change.

162
00:20:28,059 --> 00:20:42,439
For instance, if I make a decision to move away from a certain job or a certain set of friendships which I can see are not virtuous, they're not quite supporting the life I want to lead,

163
00:20:42,875 --> 00:20:47,462
That movement away may be painful because I have certain friendships.

164
00:20:48,444 --> 00:20:51,971
But in doing so, I am moving into another area.

165
00:20:52,111 --> 00:20:55,857
The decision takes me into another area of experience which does support me.

166
00:20:57,019 --> 00:21:04,113
So we can say that the friendships that I meet here and the job that I'm doing now is my punya.

167
00:21:04,232 --> 00:21:06,537
That's my merit for shifting across.

168
00:21:07,698 --> 00:21:10,801
But, in a sense, that misses the point.

169
00:21:10,863 --> 00:21:11,864
That's all well and good.

170
00:21:14,528 --> 00:21:18,252
But the real punya, the real merit, is within the heart itself.

171
00:21:19,615 --> 00:21:28,768
So that's why, when we become fully liberated, in a couple of days, you'll see that there's no more punya.

172
00:21:29,269 --> 00:21:30,770
There is no more merit to be had.

173
00:21:32,393 --> 00:21:36,439
Because the liberated person is completely full.

174
00:21:38,359 --> 00:21:42,748
They're completely contented and completely happy, so they cannot increase their punya.

175
00:21:42,768 --> 00:21:44,431
And this is what it says in the scriptures.

176
00:21:44,451 --> 00:21:45,313
You can't increase that.

177
00:21:45,512 --> 00:21:46,394
That's it, they've made it.

178
00:21:47,115 --> 00:21:50,342
Yet they still behave out of this compassionate action.

179
00:21:52,184 --> 00:21:59,659
And that's when it becomes selfless, because whether we like it or not, when we do good, we are increasing our own goodness within ourselves.

180
00:22:00,532 --> 00:22:05,680
So while we're not liberated, we do get the benefit of this punya.

181
00:22:06,319 --> 00:22:14,750
But once a person becomes liberated, then there's no more punya.

182
00:22:14,770 --> 00:22:22,221
I'm reminded of, I think it was Sister Teresa of Lisieux.

183
00:22:24,259 --> 00:22:28,906
I think it was Teresa of Lisieux, Saint Teresa of Lisieux.

184
00:22:29,567 --> 00:22:36,920
And she was asked, if everybody goes to heaven, some people have obviously been better than others.

185
00:22:38,542 --> 00:22:39,403
And everybody's in heaven.

186
00:22:40,164 --> 00:22:42,229
So how can you all be happy?

187
00:22:42,509 --> 00:22:44,972
Because some will have more happiness than others.

188
00:22:47,215 --> 00:22:49,440
Probably a bit of jealousy, you know.

189
00:22:51,309 --> 00:22:59,884
And her answer was, well, everybody gets a glass and it's completely full, but each glass is of a different size.

190
00:23:02,971 --> 00:23:13,470
Everybody gets a glass and it's completely full, but everybody has a different size, depending on their craftsmanship.

191
00:23:17,365 --> 00:23:24,453
If you look at the different arahats, if you look at the different people of the Buddha's time like Sariputta and Moggallana, then you can see that.

192
00:23:24,473 --> 00:23:36,368
You can see that quite clearly that they have different areas which for them produce, what can we say, a different type of contentment.

193
00:23:36,388 --> 00:23:41,736
So Sariputta is known as the general of the Dharma.

194
00:23:42,442 --> 00:24:11,300
so his whole interest was in understanding and it's understood that he's only second to the Buddha perhaps even equal in his understanding to the Buddha the Buddha definitely praises him as being quite exceptional in his insight and because of that because of that whole interest in understanding he doesn't develop the powers doesn't develop the powers

195
00:24:12,529 --> 00:24:23,188
Moggallana, who's the other chief disciple, isn't so interested in that angle of things but develops the powers.

196
00:24:23,208 --> 00:24:27,335
And when Moggallana asks Sariputta, why don't you develop the powers?

197
00:24:28,717 --> 00:24:30,420
Sariputta's answer is, I'm not interested.

198
00:24:32,729 --> 00:24:33,349
Not interested.

199
00:24:34,451 --> 00:24:48,151
So there's something about Sariputta's state, where he is totally content with the way he is, and he doesn't see any point in levitation, or moving from here to there, or doing amazing things.

200
00:24:49,512 --> 00:24:56,221
